<add rend="pasteon" source="#r1"> <q who="unknown" type="written"><floatingText rend="flat"><body><head>FROM ROME.</head>
<milestone unit="undeclared" rend="horbar-short-center"/>
<byline> correspondence of the N.Y. Tribune</byline>

<dateline>ROME, March 24, 1857.</dateline>
<p>Rome's bill of fare offers invariably her home&#8212;made nature, ruins, churches, galleries and studios, beside her made&#8212;dishes of shops, gossip, scandal, fashion and vanity, which many prefer; in all a profuse banquet for the wise and the foolish, from which none need go empty sway; and also food for sense and for soul, differing only in the partaking and digesting.</p> 
                                                          
<p>To <hi rend="italic">sans c&#0230;ur </hi> and fine linen people, a ride on the Appian Way, a sight of the Forum and Coliseum, St. Peter's and the Vatican, a yawn at Gibson's, Crawford's and Page's; some mosaics, pearls and scarfs; something gossipy and garrulous about the ministers, spiritual and temporal, and, by way of balancing their charities, some speculations on Crawford's state, his eulogy, epitaph and convalescence; then a Roman Punch of A.'s divorce, B.'s litigation, C.'s engagement&#8212;whether it is generally known or not, and whether she knows his intrigues; then a cigarette in the Villa Borghese, or on the Pinchio, and finally a salute at a Cardinal's reception, is the faring sumptuously everyday, and the veritable feast of reason and flow of soul, undreamed of in their arch epicurean fancies.</p>
                
<p>Once in a while, in a transcendental fit of wisdom, for instance in a fine day, when, as Emerson says, "the cattle have great and tranquil thoughts," scenting the trail of a vagrant <hi rend="italic">flaneur</hi>,  in hopes of rare and dainty game, or of finding some piquant weed for condiment or flavor, they follow by&#8212;paths into by&#8212;corners, aside from prescribed sights and guide&#8212;book routes, and praise and hug themselves in coming, all of a sudden, on a pot of cream in a cellar, or some savory herbs in a garret, or a wild duck on a shelf, all which, taking care not to heat or soil themselves, they pack into their pic&#8212;nic sacks, lauding extremely the brilliancy of their eccentricities, and wondering if ever any one won so wittingly value from their travels; entirely unsuspecting that the old Leather&#8212;Stocking hunter, who has these small stores behind is far ahead, by his sagacity and patience filling pouch with the daintiest birds, and bearing the heavier game on his back, which nourish him as loves in the heart, and truth in the head, and in their way make him too fare sumptuously everyday; finding this tent pitched under and shady tree, or a home in every vine tapestried ruin, where he may muse on all the canopy covers, in Rome and without, with no aim but to hunt God's truth and to live on God's goods, content always with the simple fare of wisdom and love which these fashionable pursuers of his trail pervert in cooking with their condiments of curiosity, vanity and worldly wisdom, till their final dish is, like a French fricassee or an Italian mayonaise, made to tickle the taste more than to nourish the strength. LeatherStocking is chary of his commerce with Fine Linen and the Grundyists in general; but occasionally, with a simple and truth-loving heart, he indulges an amicable mood, and spreads out before him, in some favorite haunt, his dainty repast, and waits till the shadows grow long in telling his tales of town and country. Sometimes, with a friend or two, in a short cut across the Campagna, we have caught a familiar nod as he hurried by, or seen his fresh footsteps up some valley, opening a vista to the mountains, or found a bouquet of first wall-flowers left at the Coliseum; or seen him stretched in the sun with a group of models, or playing the castanets to the Sartorello dancing girls, but before we arrive he is off as quick as his shadow, lost in an unexpected subterranean of the Palace of the C&#0230;sars, or next seen emerging from an unmasked columbarium in a garden of chicory, telling the gardener of the arabesque beneath, and also about some Ghiotto frescoes in a walled&#8212;off corridor in the church across the field. Anon at the Vatican, in citizen's dress, he is looking at a pure Greek bit, too mutilated for Red Book rhapsodies, but just whole enough to hold a heart or pulse; and the next we hear of him he has found something of promise in an unknown artist's studio, or is extolling something</p></body></floatingText></q></add>
 
