<body>
<p>Ruskin never saw or wrote about, and all the Royal Academicians are ignorant or blind to; regaling himself continually with tit&#8212;bits neither fashionable nor conventional, doing the socratic with the rich as boldly as with the poor, husking down all people and things to their kernel, giving the husks to the swine, sowing the good seed on good ground, and leaving the bad to rot or come to tares. Again we find him rating the Apollo, the Torso Belvidere and the Dying Gladiator at their full value, and rendering honor to whom honor is due, in the works of Raphael and Micheal Angelo, but reserving his superlatives for things better still, having a place for everything, and everything in its place, with an order astonishing and incomprehensible to those who would pile all, pell&#8212;mell, on the top shelf. Though not a lion hunger, Leather&#8212;Stocking makes the old lions cower as effectually as Gerard's sure shots; and before him Prince, the Lion of Lehore, is tame as a kid, and the lionesses, Mrs. Jamison, Mrs. Guckill and Mrs. Stowe, are as playful as maidens, and all the big bugs and little bugs take rank and make file in their order of merit, and buzz off safe as buzzards, leaving in great relief Margaret Fuller's observation on the natural history of lions, that, when seen close to, their pranks are much like those of other animals. Whether Leather Stock&#8212;ing can be called popularly speaking, a friend or an enemy, I cannot say; on some he leaves a shame&#8212;shadow, on others a glow of delight; to some he is the skeleton of their house, to others as their household god, just as their affections take him. But the most we know of this rare old wonder is from hearsay, or from occasional short encounters on his trails, or from hints gathered fresh from where he has just gone, or from rehearsals of his propensities by some fellow&#8212;companion, as at our visit to F. the other day, who never tires of his eulogy.</p>
    
<p>F. is one of Leather Stocking's cronies&#8212;more of a maniaist and less universal than he, but yet akin in loves; and so always friends that look each other in the eye. F. came a pensioner to Rome from Piedmont at the age of fifteen, and since then for forty years he has traced his designs, smoked his cigar and taken his coffee at the same little table at the Grecco, and inhabited the same high, sunless rooms in the Piazza San Pietro, looking out on the grim, vine&#8212;deviced walls connecting St. Angelo and the Vatican, spite of damp, dark and solitude, covering his cherished nest&#8212;eggs, and hatching out hints which the world steals, nurtures and is proud of, while his own brooding patience is more content and happier in the hatching than in the rearing of its offspring.</p > 
<p> For some time I had felt I ought to pay a visit to my kind old master, not that I owed him one because he ever comes to see me&#8212;for when he is off his nest he is always &#8212;but because when I go to see him he greets me cordially, and looks happy that I have not forgotten him or lost interest in what he is and does; and thinking he and his appurtenances might be among the rarest of Rome's by&#8212;way sights, I proposed to the two Misses Fine Linen to accompany me to his rooms. At 11 we enter the sun&#8212;sparking Piazza&#8212;the fountains and light stones all aglow; St. Peter's and the Vatican erect against the brights sky; the red&#8212;hot uniforms and caps and bayonets tipped with flame, making a spectacle unrivaled in brilliancy. While we are blinking our eyes in admiration, the carriage stops before the deep shadow of the Great Porte Cochere of the Palace, whose dark back rooms F. occupies. The entrance is fortress like, becoming its neighborhood to the Fort and the Vatican; a shrine, with a picture and a cross and a flicker of olive oil stands in the dim passage. The ladies stop in the court, admiring the fountain, while I run up to the first story and around the Loggia to F.'s door, where I flutter in my mind how to conciliate the old artist and obtain the grace I have come to beg for. I know he dislikes visits from others than artists or pupils, and ladies, particularly, he has a dread of. But, summoning all my amiable pleas, I jerk the wire bell&#8212;pull and pound the heavy knocker, and by and by F. shuffles out, opens the door, takes out his pipe and salutes me; and before he has time to bide me come in, I asked permission that the ladies below may accompany me. "Are they artists?" asks he. "No&#8212;yes"&#8212;I reply; "one is an authoress." "Do they or draw or paint or work in sculpture?" "No," I am forced to answer. He looks dubious and hesitating, hating to refuse me, but bored with the thought of meeting any branch of the Fine Linen family; but I plead the universality of art, and quibble the authoress into an artist. His scruples stagger into confused excuses. "They will find him</p>
